{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"41c68762-1793-4c0c-a669-5b1cae9dee30","content":"Good news — in .NET 10, `dotnet test` uses Microsoft Testing Platform **by default**. The `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` property is no longer needed; it was the .NET 9 opt-in flag that's now the default behavior.\n\nYou can simply remove that line:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_0113wWFB8ea3Tfjgth2yetpj","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-e2cf679bda0c4feebc68eaca1c7b838b/TestProject.csproj","old_str":"    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n","new_str":""},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-e2cf679bda0c4feebc68eaca1c7b838b/TestProject.csproj."}],"interactionId":"384c90db-fa60-42af-ad08-4a4d1b8bac94","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is on .NET 10 SDK and wants to know about native MTP support in `dotnet test`.\n\nIn .NET 10, `dotnet test` natively uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) as the default test runner. The `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` property was needed in .NET 9 to opt in to the MTP integration with `dotnet test`, but in .NET 10 it's the default behavior, so it's no longer needed.\n\nLet me update their project file to remove the now-unnecessary property.","outputTokens":360,"requestId":"3416:7CA0B:7500CB0:8153678:69F3FB7E"},"id":"815a28b1-a737-4beb-b9a2-39a5fca6012b","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:01:58.087Z","parentId":"147c91c3-0b09-4491-a9f6-e4ffc71ea7cc"}
